Definition 4.1. By a right $\Gamma$-$\mathcal{C}$-module category, or a right $\Gamma$-equivariant $\mathcal{C}$-module category, we mean a right $\mathcal{C}$-module category $\mathcal{D}$ equipped with a weak action $\beta\colon\Gamma\curvearrowright\mathcal{D}$ and a family of natural isomorphisms $\beta_{2}^{g}\colon\beta^{g}(X)\times\alpha^{g}(U)\to\beta^{g}(X\times U)$ compatible with $\mu$, $\eta_{\alpha}$ and $\eta_{\beta}$ in the sense that the following two diagrams commute: $\xymatrix@C=3em{(\beta^{g}(X)\times\alpha^{g}(U))\times\alpha^{g}(V)\ar[r]^{\ % \ \ \ \beta^{g}_{2}\times\iota}\ar[d]_{\mu^{\alpha^{g}(U),\alpha^{g}(V)}_{% \beta^{g}(X)}}&\beta^{g}(X\times U)\times\alpha^{g}(V)\ar[r]^{\beta^{g}_{2}}&% \beta^{g}((X\times U)\times V)\ar[d]^{\beta^{g}(\mu^{U,V}_{X})}\\ \beta^{g}(X)\times(\alpha^{g}(U)\otimes\alpha^{g}(V))\ar[r]_{\ \ \ \ \iota% \times\alpha^{g}_{2}}&\beta^{g}(X)\times\alpha^{g}(U\otimes V)\ar[r]_{\beta^{g% }_{2}}&\beta^{g}(X\times(U\otimes V))}$ $\xymatrix@C=0em{\beta^{g}(\beta^{h}(X)\times\alpha^{h}(U))\ar[d]_{\beta^{g}(% \beta_{2}^{h})}&&\beta^{g}\beta^{h}(X)\times\alpha^{g}\alpha^{h}(U)\ar[ll]_{% \beta_{2}^{g}}\ar[d]^{\eta_{\beta}^{g,h}\times\eta_{\alpha}^{g,h}}\\ \beta^{g}\beta^{h}(X\times U)\ar[dr]_{\eta_{\beta}^{g,h}}&&\beta^{gh}(X)\times% \alpha^{gh}(U)\ar[dl]^{\beta_{2}^{gh}}\\ &\beta^{gh}(X\times U).\\ }$
Definition 1.3 ([arXiv:1506.09194]). An invariant cocentral action of $\Gamma$ on $A$ is a pair $(p,\alpha)$ where • $p\colon A\rightarrow K\Gamma$ is a cocentral Hopf algebra homomorphism, • $\alpha\colon\Gamma\rightarrow\operatorname{Aut}(A)$ is an action of $\Gamma$ by Hopf algebra automorphisms on $A$, with $p\alpha_{g}=p$ for all $g\in\Gamma$. In terms of the $\Gamma$-gradings, the last condition is equivalent to $\alpha_{g}(A_{h})=A_{h}$ for all $g,h\in\Gamma$. When $(p,\alpha)$ is such an action, the graded twisting $A^{t,\alpha}$ of $A$ is the Hopf algebra $A^{t,\alpha}=\sum_{g\in\Gamma}A_{g}\otimes g\subset A\rtimes\Gamma,$ equipped with the algebra structure of the crossed product $A\rtimes\Gamma$, which we identify with $A\otimes K\Gamma$ as a linear space, and with the coalgebra structure induced by the linear isomorphism $j\colon A\to A^{t,\alpha},\quad\sum_{g}a_{g}\mapsto\sum_{g}a_{g}\otimes g.$
Definition 3.3. A $\Gamma$-$A$-comodule algebra is given by the following data: • $(R,\rho_{R}\colon R\to A\otimes R)$ is a left $A$-comodule algebra, and • $\beta\colon\Gamma\rightarrow\operatorname{Aut}(R)$ is an action of $\Gamma$ on $R$ by algebra automorphisms, such that $\rho_{R}\beta_{g}=(\alpha_{g}\otimes\beta_{g})\rho_{R}$ for any $g\in\Gamma$.
Definition 1.1 (\citelist[MR1228767][MR1334152]). A sequence of Hopf algebra homomorphisms $K\to B\overset{i}{\to}A\overset{p}{\to}L\to K$ is said to be exact if the following conditions hold: (i) $i$ is injective, $p$ is surjective, and $pi(b)=\varepsilon(b)1$, for any $b\in B$; (ii) $\ker p=Ai(B)^{+}=i(B)^{+}A$, where $i(B)^{+}=i(B)\cap\ker(\varepsilon)$; (iii) the image of $i$ is equal to the coinvariants of $L$, that is, $i(B)=A^{\mathrm{co}K\Gamma}=\{a\in A\mid(\operatorname{id}\otimes p)\Delta(a)=% a\otimes 1\}={{}^{\mathrm{co}K\Gamma}A}=\{a\in A\mid(p\otimes\operatorname{id}% )\Delta(a)=1\otimes a\}.$
Definition 3.7. We say that an algebraic subgroup $H\subset\mathrm{GL}(2)$ is $q$-admissible if $\hat{\Gamma}_{q}\subset H$ and $\alpha_{g}(H)=H$.
Definition 5.4. We say that a natural transformation $\eta\in\hat{\mathcal{C}}(U,V)$ is absolutely harmonic if $P_{s}(\eta)=\eta$ for all $s\in\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 4.10 ([MR1815142]). Given a weak action $(\beta,\eta_{\beta})$ of $\Gamma$ on a category $\mathcal{D}$, a $\Gamma$-invariant, or $\Gamma$-equivariant, object is a pair $(X,\zeta)$ consisting of an object $X\in\mathcal{D}$ and a family $\zeta$ of isomorphisms $\zeta^{g}\colon\beta^{g}(X)\to X$ such that the diagrams $\xymatrix@C=4em{\beta^{g}\beta^{h}(X)\ar[r]^{\beta^{g}(\zeta^{h})}\ar[d]_{\eta% _{\beta}^{g,h}}&\beta^{g}(X)\ar[d]^{\zeta^{g}}\\ \beta^{gh}(X)\ar[r]_{\zeta^{gh}}&X}$ commute for $g,h\in\Gamma$. The category of $\Gamma$-invariant objects is denoted by $\mathcal{D}^{\Gamma}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\rho_{V}\colon V\to A\otimes V$ be a left $A$-comodule, and $\beta_{V}=\beta$ be a linear representation of $\Gamma$ on $V$. We say that $(V,\beta)$ is $\Gamma$-equivariant, or that it is a $\Gamma$-$A$-comodule, if $\rho$ is $\Gamma$-equivariant with respect to $\beta$ and $\alpha\otimes\beta$. We denote the category of $\Gamma$-$A$-comodules with the $\Gamma$-linear and $A$-colinear maps as morphisms by $\operatorname{Comod}(A,\Gamma,\alpha)$.
