Definition 1.3. The object $\Ar(\simCat)$ is the object of arrows of the internal $\simCat$, whose object of objects $\Ob(\simCat)$ is $\nno$. Composition is defined as ordinary function composition.
Definition 2.2. An is a pairs of set of morphisms $(L,R)$ of an enriched category with the following properties. • A morphism belong to $L$ if and only if it has the left lifting property with respect all to members of $R$. • A morphism belong to $R$ if and only if it has the right lifting property with respect all to members of $L$. • Every morphism factors as a member of $R$ following a member of $L$. A morphism $f:X\to Y$ of an $\mathcal{A}$-enriched category $\mathcal{C}$ has the right lifting property with respect to a morphism $g:I\to J$–and $g$ has the left lifting property with respect to $f$–if the morphism $\left\langle f_{!},g^{*}\right\rangle=\left\langle\mathcal{C}(\id_{J},f),% \mathcal{C}(g,\id_{X}))\right\rangle$ which is the factorization of the span $\mathcal{C}(\id_{J},f)$, $\mathcal{C}(g,\id_{X})$ through the pullback cone of $\mathcal{C}(\id_{I},f)$ and $\mathcal{C}(g,\id_{Y})$ is a split epimorphism. $\xy(34,20)*+{\mathcal{C}(I,X)}="top",(0,10)*+{\mathcal{C}(J,X)}="left",(24,10)% *+{\bullet}="middle",(44,10)*+{\mathcal{C}(I,Y)}="right",(34,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(% J,Y)}="bottom"\ar^{\mathcal{C}(g,\id_{X})}"left";"top"\ar@{.>}|(.6){\left% \langle f_{!},g^{*}\right\rangle}"left";"middle"\ar_{\mathcal{C}(\id_{J},f)}"% left";"bottom"\ar"middle";"bottom"\ar"middle";"top"\ar^{(}.6){\mathcal{C}(\id_% {I},f)}"top";"right"\ar_{(}.6){\mathcal{C}(g,\id_{Y})}"bottom";"right"\endxy$ A section of $\left\langle f_{!},g^{*}\right\rangle$ is a .
Definition 3.9. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a $\Pi$-pretopos with a natural number object $\nno$. The successor morphism $s:\nno\to\nno$ induces an endofunctor $s^{*}$ of $\mathcal{A}/\nno$. A is a morphism $f:X\to s^{*}(X)$ in $\mathcal{A}/\nno$. A morphism of cochains $(X,f)\to(Y,g)$ is a morphism $h:X\to Y$ such that $s^{*}(h)\circ f=g\circ h$. For every object $Y$ of $\mathcal{A}$ there is a constant family $\nno^{*}(Y)$ and a canonical isomorphism $\nno^{*}(Y)\simeq s^{*}(\nno^{*}(Y))$ which makes $\nno^{*}(Y)$ a cochain. The of a cochain $(X,g)$ is a cochain morphism $\omega(g):(X,f)\to\nno^{*}Y$ such that for every other morphism $k:(X,f)\to\nno^{*}Z$ there is a unique morphism $l:Z\to Y$ such that $s^{*}(l)\circ\omega(g)=k$.
Definition 2.7. A is a composition of an acyclic fibration following an acyclic cofibration. Here, an acyclic fibration is a morphism that has the right lifting property with respect to all cofibrations; an acyclic cofibration is a cofibration has the right lifting property with respect to all fibrations.
